## üî£ NUMBERS AND MATH

set /a = Arithmetic mode

It tells the set command to evaluate the right side as a math expression instead of just plain text.

```bat
SET /A x=5+3          :: 8
SET /A x=10/2         :: 5
SET /A x=5%%3         :: 2 (modulus)
SET /A x=(4+6)*2      :: 20
ECHO %x%

| Operator  | Meaning             | Example         | Result |   |
| --------- | ------------------- | --------------- | ------ | - |
| `+`       | addition            | `set /a x=3+2`  | 5      |   |
| `-`       | subtraction         | `set /a x=10-4` | 6      |   |
| `*`       | multiply            | `set /a x=3*5`  | 15     |   |
| `/`       | integer division    | `set /a x=7/2`  | 3      |   |
| `%`       | modulus (remainder) | `set /a x=7%%3` | 1      |   |
| `<<` `>>` | bit shifts          | `set /a x=2<<3` | 16     |   |
| `&` `     | ` `^`               | bitwise ops     | ‚Äî      | ‚Äî |

```

```bat
:: Increment/Decrement
SET /A count+=1
SET /A count-=1
```

